          "body": "The covenant made in 9:15 is sealed by an oath sworn in the Lord's name — not Joshua's private agreement but a formal covenant ratified by the leaders of the congregation. Three days later the truth surfaces (9:16). The congregation's reaction is to grumble against the leaders (9:18) — a verb (*lun*) that carries Exodus/Numbers associations of wilderness murmuring (cf. Exodus 16:2; Numbers 14:2). But the leaders hold. Their reasoning is explicitly theological: 'We have sworn to them by the Lord the God of Israel, and now we cannot touch them' (9:19). The ground for holding the oath is not that it was well-made but that the Lord's name was invoked in its making. To break it would not merely dishonor the Gibeonites; it would profane the divine name. Numbers 30:2 states the principle directly: a man who swears an oath by the Lord shall not violate his word. The leaders' fidelity to a foolish oath is not moral paralysis; it is the recognition that God's name is heavier than their mistake."
