          "title": "Servitude at the altar — fear transformed into proximity",
          "body": "The chapter's final resolution is a study in providence working through human failure. Joshua's curse assigns the Gibeonites to hew wood and draw water 'for the house of my God' (9:23) and 'for the congregation and for the altar of the Lord, to this day, in the place which He would choose' (9:27). The place He would choose is Jerusalem — and Kiriath-jearim, one of the Gibeonite cities (9:17), will become the resting place of the ark (1 Samuel 7:1-2). What began as survival-fear ends as permanent liturgical proximity. The Gibeonites who lied their way into the covenant ended up closer to Israel's worship than many Israelites ever came. Calvin observed that God often turns the errors of His people to purposes they did not intend; Joshua 9 is one of the clearest examples in the historical books. The Gibeonites' descendants served at the temple — and the Nethinim (temple servants) of Ezra 2:43-54 and Nehemiah 7:46-56 are almost certainly their institutional heirs."
