        "excerpt": "So the men of Israel took some of their provisions, and did not ask for the counsel of the Lord.",
        "body": "Verse 14 is the hinge of the entire chapter and one of the most theologically compressed sentences in the book of Joshua. The first clause — 'the men of Israel took some of their provisions' — describes a reasonable act of due diligence. They examined the physical evidence the Gibeonites presented. This is what discerning leaders do. The second clause — 'and did not ask for the counsel of the Lord' — is the fatal omission. The two clauses sit side by side without connective commentary. The narrator does not editorialize; he simply places the investigation and the failure together and lets the juxtaposition indict.\n\nThe phrase 'ask the counsel of the Lord' (*sha'al et-peh YHWH*, literally 'inquire of the mouth of the Lord') would have meant consulting the Urim and Thummim through the priest Eleazar (cf. Numbers 27:21; Joshua 17:4; 18:8-10 where the same vocabulary appears for land allocation decisions). The mechanism was available. The war camp at Gilgal was the place where Israel had renewed the covenant (5:2-9) and celebrated Passover (5:10-12). The ark was there. The priest was there. The means of inquiry was not absent; the willingness to use it was.\n\nWhy did they not ask? The text does not say. But the narrative implies that the physical evidence satisfied them. The bread was crumbled; the wineskins were cracked; the sandals were worn. What else would you need to know? This is the epistemology that 9:14 is warning against: the evidence that satisfies the eye may be the very evidence that has been manufactured to satisfy the eye. Only the Lord could see through the staged props to the Gibeonite city six miles northwest of Jerusalem.\n\nSwindoll notes in his commentary on Joshua that the chapter's warning is not against using evidence — it is against using evidence as a substitute for prayer. The men of Israel did not fail to look; they failed to kneel. That is the chapter's precise, singular indictment, and everything in verses 16-27 flows from it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shaal et-peh YHWH* — 'to inquire of the mouth of the Lord'; a technical phrase for priestly oracle consultation (Numbers 27:21). *Nasi* (leaders/princes, 9:15) — tribal representatives with full legal authority to covenant on the congregation's behalf."
